    "analysis": "Previous steps:\n- Aggregated metrics showed many global-P95==0 series (likely sparse) causing false positives; credible metric anomalies are in socket KPIs across multiple services (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice and frontend), with checkoutservice and several others showing sustained socket values at or above global P95 during the incident window. \n- Trace error_rate series were all P95==0, so they produced spurious anomalies and cannot be used as-is to localize the fault.\n- According to the workflow, we now need to use trace duration metrics to find latency anomalies along service call chains (duration_mean or duration_p95). These duration anomalies can help identify which service in the call chain is the most downstream faulty service and thus the root-cause component among the candidate services.\nWhat can be derived: socket issues are suspicious and affect many candidate services. To pick the root cause among the allowed components (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice), we must check trace duration metrics inside the incident window using global thresholds computed from the full trace series (not window-filtered).",
