    "instruction": "Load log.csv and error_logs.csv; parse timestamps with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). 1) For log.csv compute the global P95 of 'value' for each (cmdb_id, log_name) across the entire file (do NOT filter by time). 2) Filter log.csv to the incident window 2024-01-19 17:51:58 UTC → 2024-01-19 18:21:58 UTC. 3) For each (cmdb_id, log_name) in the window compute: anomaly_count = number of points where value >= global_p95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc among those points, max_value_in_window, p95_value (from step 1), total_points_in_window. Return rows with anomaly_count > 0 sorted by anomaly_count desc then by (max_value_in_window / p95_value) desc. Limit to top 20 rows and present as a compact CSV-like table with columns: cmdb_id,log_name,anomaly_count,earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc,max_value_in_window,p95_value,total_points_in_window. Also return a single-line summary giving the row count of error_logs.csv and, if nonzero, up to 5 sample rows (timestamp_utc,cmdb_id,message)."
}

